[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

This would be an ideal hand to open 1NT - well, it would be with one less point. But with 18 you are too strong to open 1NT so you open 1\C. Partner responds 1\S.  

<b>DO NOT</b> fall into the trap of supporting partner's \Ss just because you have such nice help for him. He might have a 4-card suit. Instead, just describe your hand by jumping to 2NT, showing a balanced hand with 18-19 points. Partner now bids 3NT and you play it there.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:QJ6.AK7.Q864.AK8 53.T632.JT95.QJ2 KT9742.QJ5.3.743 A8.984.AK72.T965"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1D pass 1S pass 2NT pass 3S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "3969570423bd82d757846bb9c1cab594218ffca28ccb6c3078ae9e1b250bbf83"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/minor_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

You open 1\D and partner responds 1\S. What is your next bid? 

Do not support what may be a 4-card suit with only 3 cards. Instead, jump to 2NT, showing 18-19, balanced. Partner rebids the \Ss. What do you say next? 

Partner shows a minimum hand, but with 6 \Ss. 3NT is very tempting, and might work out fine, but with 9 \Ss it is probably better to play the suit game. So you bid 4\S and everybody passes.

Bidding 4\S was a good choice. It makes easily, yet 3NT might have gone down.}

